</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="137" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="137">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="137">
The three species belonging to this subgenus are large, robust moths with simple ochreous-brownish or purplish-blackish-brown (generally unicolorous but sometimes, individually, contrasting) colouration and regular pattern, somewhat resembling certain forms of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Apamea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Apamea monoglypha" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="137" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="monoglypha">Apamea monoglypha</taxonomicName>
(Hufnagel, 1766).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="137">In the male genitalia, the saccular processes are simple, short or acute, symmetrical, with prominent tuft of specialised setae on the right side. Vesica is tubular, relatively short and retroflexed, with only a short fascia of cornuti subterminally.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="137">In the female genitalia, the appendix bursae is slightly prominent only, the corpus bursae has two short longitudinal signa.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="137" type="etymology">
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="137">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="137">
The name refers to the relative simplicity of colouration and configuration of male genitalia as opposed to the huge majority of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Polia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Polia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="137" phylum="Nemertea" rank="genus">Polia</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="Poliina" lsidName="Poliina" pageId="4" pageNumber="137" rank="subTribe" subTribe="Poliina">Poliina</taxonomicName>
, respectively.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
